>>
>>RSA can be attacked in an indirect way.  If one considers RSA to be
>>covering the actual data with two envelopes, one for the sender and
>>one for the receiver, then following indirect signatures can be
>>obtained.
>>
>>If the outer envelope is for the sender, the active attacker can strip
>>sender's signature and sign it himself/herself thus masquerading as
>>an originator.  If the outer envelope is for the receiver, the
>>receiver if compromised or if unethical can strip his/her envelope
>>and obtain an envelope with sender's signature on it.  The
>>receiver can then re route the message with some one else as the
>>intended recipient.
>>
>>These two attacks destroy the assurance of the identities of the 
>>communicating entities. (jees! then what to believe, especially if
>>sender and receiver identities are not in the message too)

gec@nice.usergroup.ethz.ch (Germano Caronni) observes in
